In Japanese histories, he will be recorded as Emperor Showa, the name he chose for his reign soon after he became emperor in 1926. Now this year is Heisei 1. The year 1927 was Showa 2, and 1989 was Showa 64 until Hirohito's death on Jan 7. It means Enlightened Peace, and has been succeeded by Heisei, or Achieving Peace, the name the government chose for the reign of Hirohito's son Akihito a few hours after the emperor died Jan 7. In Japan, years are numbered according to the emperor's tenure on the throne. 